context: The Aravalli Range runs across the state from the southwest peak Guru Shikhar (Mount Abu), which is <a0_0><b5_0>1,722<a0_0/> m in height<b5_0/>, to Khetri in the northeast. This range divides the state into <a1_0><b6_0>60%<a1_0/> in the northwest of the range and 40% in the southeast<b6_0/>. The northwest tract is <b9_0>sandy and unproductive with little water<b9_0/> but improves gradually from desert land in the far west and northwest to comparatively fertile and habitable land towards the east. The area includes the Thar Desert. The south-eastern area, higher in elevation (<a2_0>100 to 350 m above sea level<a2_0/>) and more fertile, has a very diversified topography. in the south lies the hilly tract of Mewar. In the southeast, a large area within the districts of <a3_0>Kota and Bundi<a3_0/> forms a tableland. To the northeast of these districts is a rugged region (badlands) following the line of <a4_0>the Chambal River<a4_0/>. Farther north the country levels out; the flat plains of the northeastern Bharatpur district are part of <b7_0>an alluvial basin<b7_0/>. <b8_0>Merta City<b8_0/> lies in the geographical center of Rajasthan.
